Area: Anchorage; Matanuska Valley
Description:
['As temperatures climb into the 30s and 40s this afternoon, melting
snow has resulted in water collecting on area roads. Temperatures
will drop into the 20s overnight, causing water on the roads
to refreeze and form an icy surface. This may result in hazardous
conditions, especially during the Wednesday morning commute.
Motorists are urged to use caution while traveling. For the latest
road conditions call 5 1 1 or visit 511.alaska.gov.']

Area: Matanuska Valley
Description:
['The following message is transmitted at the request of the
Hatcher Pass Avalanche Center.', '
...THE HATCHER PASS AVALANCHE CENTER HAS ISSUED AN AVALANCHE
WARNING...', '* WHAT...The avalanche danger is high. Very dangerous avalanche
conditions exist. Travel in avalanche terrain is NOT recommended', '* WHERE...Skeetawk / mile 11 to Independence Mine, including Gold
Mint and Archangel Valley', '* WHEN...In effect from Tuesday 700 AKST to Wednesday 700 AKST.', '* IMPACTS...An additional 2 to 3 inches of SWE and 18 to 24 inches
of snow has accumulated over the last 24hrs. Snowfall should
taper by 6pm Tuesday. Large to very large human triggered
avalanches are very likely and natural avalanches are likely on
slopes steeper than 30 degrees. Debris from avalanches above may
run into valley bottoms.', '* PRECAUTIONARY / PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS..Travel in avalanche
terrain is not recommended. Backcountry travelers should stay
off of and out from underneath slopes steeper than 30 degrees.
Avalanches may run long distances. Avoid avalanche terrain.
Consult http://www.hpavalanche.org/ or www.avalanche.org for
more detailed information. The Hatcher Pass Road remains closed
at mile 11 due to avalanche activity.', '', 'For more information visit hpavalanche.org.']

Area: Surprise Valley California; Lassen-Eastern Plumas-Eastern Sierra Counties; Greater Lake Tahoe Area; Mono; Mineral and Southern Lyon Counties; Greater Lake Tahoe Area; Greater Reno-Carson City-Minden Area; Western Nevada Basin and Range including Pyramid Lake; Northern Washoe County
Description:
['* An intense band of lake effect snow from Pyramid Lake has
brought copious snow totals to portions of the Greater
Reno/Sparks region. Early morning reports of several inches up
to a foot, highest totals closest to the southwest side of
Pyramid Lake into Spanish Springs, have been reported. A lighter
lake effect band off Tahoe brought snow to the Basin overnight
as well. The morning commute is going to be a mess once again
due to snow and ice. Please slow down and allow plenty of extra
time!', '* This snow is light and powdery and could be prone to blowing and
drifting with reductions in visibility possible, even after the
falling snow ends. The cold temperatures could also keep area
roads and walkways snow covered and icy into the late morning
hours when the sun should help to melt things out. Be sure to
check with CalTrans and NDOT for the latest road conditions
before heading out.', '* A cold air mass will give us the potential to see some of the
coldest temperatures of the season thus far. High temperatures
today will be even colder than yesterday, with a brisk north
wind dropping wind chills into the teens and single digits in
valleys and well below zero in the mountains. Coldest night of
the week expected tonight with widespread teen and single digit
low temperatures, and below zero temperatures in colder valleys.']

Tree limbs could be blown down and a few power outages may

sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor
plumbing.']

Description:
['As of 6AM, satellite and surface obs show areas of dense fog
moving across West Central and Southwest Florida. This is expected
to last for the next couple hours before clearing.', 'Visibilities have dropped to less then one mile, with some
locations likely dropping to a few hundred yards or less.', 'Motorists, especially those on major highways, should prepare to
encounter reduced visibility in fog. When driving in fog, reduce
your speed, use only your low beam headlights, and leave extra
distance between your vehicle and the one in front of you. The fog
is expected to burn off around 9 AM.']

Area: Inland Volusia; Northern Lake County; Orange; Seminole; Osceola; Coastal Volusia; Southern Lake County
Description:
['At 440 AM, surface observations, satellite imagery and traffic
cameras showed dense fog developing across portions of Volusia,
Seminole, Lake, western Orange and Osceola counties. The fog is
expected to persist past sunrise.', 'Visibilities will drop to less then one mile, with some locations
likely dropping to a few hundred yards or less. If visibilities
lower and become more widespread, then a Dense Fog Advisory will
be needed.', 'Motorists, especially those on major highways such as the Florida
turnpike, should prepare to encounter reduced visibility in fog.
When driving in fog, reduce your speed, use only your low beam
headlights, and leave extra distance between your vehicle and the
one in front of you. The fog is expected to burn off around 9 AM.']

Description:
['The National Weather Service in Peachtree City has issued a', '* Flash Flood Warning for...
Catoosa County in northwestern Georgia...
Dade County in northwestern Georgia...
Walker County in northwestern Georgia...
Whitfield County in northwestern Georgia...', '* Until 800 AM EST Wednesday.', '* At 156 AM EST, Doppler radar indicated thunderstorms producing
heavy rain across the warned area. Between 0.5 and 1 inch of rain
has fallen. Additional rainfall amounts of 1 to 1.5 inches are
possible in the warned area in the next few hours. Flash flooding
is ongoing or expected to begin shortly.', 'HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by thunderstorms.', 'SOURCE...Radar.', 'IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, urban
areas, highways, streets and underpasses as well as
other poor drainage and low-lying areas.', '* Some locations that will experience flash flooding include...
Dalton, Lafayette, Ringgold, Trenton, Fort Oglethorpe, Rossville,
Chickamauga, Varnell, Lookout Mountain, Tunnel Hill, Cohutta, Rock
Spring, Beaumont, Blue Spring, Noble, Wood Station, Boynton,
Fairview, Indian Springs and Naomi.']

Description:
['* WHAT...Moderate to heavy mixed precipitation, mainly freezing
rain and some sleet. Ice accumulations one quarter of an inch
or more, with some minor accumulations of sleet. The highest
freezing rain accumulations are expected to be from the Ozark
Foothills to far Western Kentucky.', '* WHERE...All of southeast Missouri, the Purchase Area of western
Kentucky and southern Illinois generally west of Interstate 57
and 24.', '* WHEN...From 12 PM today to 6 PM Thursday.', '* IMPACTS...Scattered power outages and some tree damage are
likely due to the ice. Travel could be hazardous. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Two rounds of wintry precipitation can be
expected. The first will enter Southeast Missouri this
afternoon and spread across all of the warning area for the
evening and overnight hours. The second will be from midday
Thursday on through the afternoon across the Ozark Foothills of
Missouri into southwest Illinois. The rest of the warning area
should see temperatures rise above freezing Thursday, and switch
the precipitation to just rain.']

Area: La Salle, IL
Description:
['* WHAT...Near bankfull conditions and flooding caused by an ice jam
are expected.', '* WHERE...Fox River at and near Dayton.', '* WHEN...From early this morning until further notice.', '* IMPACTS...At 12.0 feet, the river begins to overflow banks in the
lowest areas.', "* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 2:00 AM CST Wednesday the stage was 10.8 feet. Also at
2:00 AM CST, emergency management reported that some ice had
broken free from an ice jam near the Dayton Dam. Some of this
ice was recollecting downstream along the Fox River in
Ottawa. Minor flooding of the Fox River Park had been
reported. In addition, there remains a large amount of ice
upstream of the Dayton Dam up to Wedron. With ongoing river
rises due to Tuesday's rainfall, there may continue to be
some immediate riverside flooding of low-lying areas due to
ice jams.
- Forecast...If any solid ice jams are reported that would
induce greater flooding, a river Flood Warning for the lower
Fox River will be issued.
- Action stage is 11.0 feet.
- Flood stage is 12.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood"]

It will then fall below flood stage Wednesday, March 2 to

Description:
['After a brief break in the precipitation across the region today,
the next wave of precipitation is forecast to move into the region
this evening and into the overnight hours. As this precipitation
moves into the region, surface temperatures will drop to near
freezing across southern Indiana and over portions of far northern
Kentucky. The rain may mix with or change over to a period of
freezing rain tonight. Some light icing accumulations will be
possible, mainly north of the Ohio River in southern Indiana. At
this time there is considerable uncertainty in whether icing will
occur in areas south of the Ohio River.', 'Forecasters at the National Weather Service will continue to look
over data later this morning and this afternoon. It is possible
that a Winter Weather Advisory may be issued later today for
portions of southern Indiana and northern Kentucky if later data
suggests a higher threat of icing.', 'Stay tuned to NOAA Weather Radio and your local media for the
latest updates.']

Description:
['After a brief break in the precipitation across the region today,
the next wave of precipitation is forecast to move into the region
this evening and into the overnight hours. As this precipitation
moves into the region, surface temperatures will drop to near
freezing across southern Indiana and over portions of far northern
Kentucky. The rain may mix with or change over to a period of
freezing rain tonight. Some light icing accumulations will be
possible, mainly north of the Ohio River in southern Indiana. At
this time there is considerable uncertainty in whether icing will
occur in areas south of the Ohio River.', 'Forecasters at the National Weather Service will continue to look
over data later this morning and this afternoon. It is possible
that a Winter Weather Advisory may be issued later today for
portions of southern Indiana and northern Kentucky if later data
suggests a higher threat of icing.', 'Stay tuned to NOAA Weather Radio and your local media for the
latest updates.']

Description:
['* An intense band of lake effect snow from Pyramid Lake has
brought copious snow totals to portions of the Greater
Reno/Sparks region. Early morning reports of several inches up
to a foot, highest totals closest to the southwest side of
Pyramid Lake into Spanish Springs, have been reported. A lighter
lake effect band off Tahoe brought snow to the Basin overnight
as well. The morning commute is going to be a mess once again
due to snow and ice. Please slow down and allow plenty of extra
time!', '* This snow is light and powdery and could be prone to blowing and
drifting with reductions in visibility possible, even after the
falling snow ends. The cold temperatures could also keep area
roads and walkways snow covered and icy into the late morning
hours when the sun should help to melt things out. Be sure to
check with CalTrans and NDOT for the latest road conditions
before heading out.', '* A cold air mass will give us the potential to see some of the
coldest temperatures of the season thus far. High temperatures
today will be even colder than yesterday, with a brisk north
wind dropping wind chills into the teens and single digits in
valleys and well below zero in the mountains. Coldest night of
the week expected tonight with widespread teen and single digit
low temperatures, and below zero temperatures in colder valleys.']

Description:
['* WHAT...Flooding caused by rain, snowmelt, and an ice jam is
occurring.', '* WHERE...A portion of central New Hampshire, including the
following county, Sullivan. Sugar River in West Claremont.', '* WHEN...Until 1115 AM EST.', '* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Streams
continue to rise due to excess runoff from earlier rainfall and
continuing snowmelt. Depending on ice behavior, any release of the
ice jam could result in sudden rises of water, leading to a rapid
flooding situation.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 710 AM EST, An ice jam locked in place in West Claremont
is causing water to rise on the Sugar River. Increased runoff
due to rain and snowmelt will continue to allow for increased
rises on the river over the next 12 hours. Flooding is
already occurring in the warned area and is expected to
continue until the ice jam releases. Between 0.5 and 0.8
inches of rain have fallen. Additional snowmelt is expected
through today.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Claremont.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood']

Description:
['A strong cold front will move into the Western Low Rolling Plains
today, and through the rest of West Texas and Southeast New Mexico
tonight. Freezing drizzle will be possible behind the front after
midnight tonight, mainly over the Western Low Rolling Plains, as
well as the northern and central Permian Basin. This may mix with
sleet Wednesday night and Thursday morning as an upper level
disturbance arrives over the region.  At this time, ice
accumulations are expected to be light...under a tenth of an
inch...and mainly on elevated surfaces, bridges, and overpasses.
Motorists should exercise caution by slowing down and increasing
following distances.']

Area: Northern Oregon Cascades; Cascades in Lane County; South Washington Cascades
Description:
['A late season push of arctic air is spreading into the region this
morning, along with increasing east to northeast winds.
Temperatures have already fallen into the lower to middle teens
this morning on the Cascade passes, trending toward single digits
for the ski resort elevations. Combined with winds gusting up to
40 mph, the resulting wind chills will be below zero at times for
the passes through Wednesday.', 'Even colder wind chills are likely for the higher ski resort
elevations, where the combination of single digit temperatures and
blustery winds will make it feel like 10 to 15 degrees below
zero. Such wind chills can cause frostbite on exposed skin within
30 minutes.', 'Anyone heading up to the Cascades should be prepared for colder
temperatures than usual. Drivers should be sure to have a winter
weather kit in their vehicle, along with blankets and plenty of
fuel.']

possible.', '* WHERE...Portions of Alabama and southern middle Tennessee,

DeKalb, Franklin AL, Jackson, Lauderdale, Lawrence, Limestone,

creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Widespread showers and thunderstorms will develop along a

Tuesday evening. The front will drift slowly southeastward

inches will lead to a high risk for both areal and flash
flooding.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood']

Description:
['An arriving Canadian airmass will lead to rapidly falling
temperatures overnight tonight. Areas across the southern Edwards
Plateau and Hill Country will see temperatures fall to and just
below freezing by sunrise Wednesday morning. High amounts of
moisture near the surface, combined with a disturbance passing to
our north could lead to light drizzle across the region. With
temperatures near and potentially below freezing, it is possible
that some of the drizzle could freeze and stick to branches and
other exposed surfaces. With the recent warmth, icing of
sidewalks and roadways is not anticipated.']

into early Wednesday morning.', 'Motorists, especially on South Padre Island and the Causeway, are
urged to reduce speed, use low beam headlights, and avoid
following other vehicles too closely.']

Description:
['A strong cold front will move into the Western Low Rolling Plains
today, and through the rest of West Texas and Southeast New Mexico
tonight. Freezing drizzle will be possible behind the front after
midnight tonight, mainly over the Western Low Rolling Plains, as
well as the northern and central Permian Basin. This may mix with
sleet Wednesday night and Thursday morning as an upper level
disturbance arrives over the region.  At this time, ice
accumulations are expected to be light...under a tenth of an
inch...and mainly on elevated surfaces, bridges, and overpasses.
Motorists should exercise caution by slowing down and increasing
following distances.']

commute on Friday.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snow will move into the area after midnight

daybreak. The snow will become steadier as the morning

exist Friday morning through Friday afternoon, which will result
in difficult travel conditions.']

Area: Northern Oregon Cascades; Cascades in Lane County; South Washington Cascades
Description:
['A late season push of arctic air is spreading into the region this
morning, along with increasing east to northeast winds.
Temperatures have already fallen into the lower to middle teens
this morning on the Cascade passes, trending toward single digits
for the ski resort elevations. Combined with winds gusting up to
40 mph, the resulting wind chills will be below zero at times for
the passes through Wednesday.', 'Even colder wind chills are likely for the higher ski resort
elevations, where the combination of single digit temperatures and
blustery winds will make it feel like 10 to 15 degrees below
zero. Such wind chills can cause frostbite on exposed skin within
30 minutes.', 'Anyone heading up to the Cascades should be prepared for colder
temperatures than usual. Drivers should be sure to have a winter
weather kit in their vehicle, along with blankets and plenty of
fuel.']

Area: Ashland, WI
Description:
['The following message is transmitted at the request of the
Ashland County Sheriffs Office.', 'This is an urgent message from the Ashland County Communications
Center. US Highway 2 remains closed between State Highway 112 in
the City of Ashland and State Highway 13 North in the Town of
Eileen due to extreme weather conditions. Motorists must use the
designated State Highway 137 alternate route. All travel is
discouraged. Tune to local radio or television stations for
further details.', 'Closure to remain in effect until Wednesday morning or until
conditions improve.']
